Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows one idiomatic way to expose a C++ iterator (the one that libpcapng supplies) to OCaml.  
The binding lets the OCaml programmer write

```ocaml
let () =
  let p = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  Pcapng.iter (fun frame ->
      Printf.printf "frame %d, %f s, %d bytes\n"
        !i frame.length (Unix.gettimeofday ());
      incr i)
    p;
  Pcapng.close p
```

The core ideas are:

* an abstract OCaml type `t` that holds a pointer to a C++ `Reader` object;
* a *custom block* with a finaliser that deletes the C++ object when the OCaml value is GC‑collected;
* a thin OCaml wrapper (`pcapng.ml`) that forwards calls to the C stubs;
* a C‑stub file written as **C++** (`pcapng_stubs.cpp`) that uses the OCaml C‑API to:
  * allocate the custom block,
  * convert a C++ `frame` into an OCaml record,
  * invoke a user‑supplied OCaml closure for every frame,
  * propagate OCaml exceptions back to the caller,
  * expose a few convenience functions (`next`, `fold`, …).

All the code you need is bundled in the three files below.  
You can copy‑paste them into a directory, compile the library, and start using it immediately.

---

## 1. The public OCaml interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli  –  public interface for the libpcapng OCaml binding
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** A handle to an opened pcapng file.  The value is opaque – it is
    created by {!open_file} and must be released with {!close}. *)
type t

(** A single frame (packet) extracted from the file.  The fields are
    deliberately simple so that they can be built without extra
    allocations in the C stub. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp : float;   (** seconds since the Unix epoch (as reported by the file) *)
  length    : int;     (** captured length of the frame *)
  data      : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes *)
}

(** Exception raised when the underlying C++ library reports an error. *)
exception Error of string

(** Open a pcapng file and obtain a handle.  Raises [Error] on failure. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Release a handle.  After a call to [close] the handle must not be used
    again.  It is also safe to rely on the automatic finaliser, but calling
    it explicitly is good practice for deterministic resource release. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames, invoking the supplied OCaml function on each
    frame.  The iteration stops as soon as the function raises an exception,
    which is then propagated to the caller. *)
val iter : (frame -> unit) -> t -> unit

(** Fold over the frames.  The function is called with the accumulator and
    the current frame, and its result becomes the new accumulator.  The
    final accumulator is returned.  Exceptions are propagated as with [iter]. *)
val fold : ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> t -> 'a

(** Return the next frame, or [None] if the end of the file has been reached.
    This is a low‑level primitive; most users will prefer [iter] or [fold]. *)
val next : t -> frame option

(** Reset the iterator to the beginning of the file.  Useful together with
    [next] when you want to scan the file more than once. *)
val reset : t -> unit
```

